# Scribe

Scribe is a lightweight Windows-first SQL\*Plus session recorder. It launches SQL\*Plus as a child process, records a live raw transcript, supports `/scribe` internal commands, and stores session data on disk — using only the Python standard library.

## Quick Start

```powershell
python -m scribe
```

Pass SQL\*Plus arguments after `--`:

```powershell
python -m scribe -- scott/tiger@orcl
```

Use a custom SQL\*Plus executable:

```powershell
python -m scribe --sqlplus C:\oracle\product\11.2.0\dbhome_1\BIN\sqlplus.exe -- scott/tiger@orcl
```

If SQL\*Plus requires elevation, relaunch Scribe through UAC:

```powershell
python -m scribe --elevate -- scott/tiger@orcl
```

Password prompts are detected automatically and masked with `∎`.

## Startup Options

| Flag | Description |
|---|---|
| `--config PATH` | Path to config file (default: `scribe.config.json`) |
| `--sqlplus PATH` | SQL\*Plus executable path (overrides config) |
| `--elevate` | Relaunch Scribe in an elevated Windows Terminal window |
| `--` | Delimiter for arguments forwarded to SQL\*Plus |

## Internal Commands

Internal commands are consumed by Scribe and are not forwarded to SQL\*Plus.

| Command | Description |
|---|---|
| `/scribe status` | Show session info (id, paths, counts) |
| `/scribe note <text>` | Attach a note to the current session |
| `/scribe export` | Export commands to Markdown |
| `/scribe search <term>` | Search past session transcripts |
| `/scribe history` | Show recent commands |
| `/scribe bootstrap` | Re-run SQL\*Plus setup commands |
| `/scribe help` | Show this help |

## Configuration

Default configuration is created at `scribe.config.json` on first run:

```json
{
  "sqlplus_path": "sqlplus",
  "sessions_dir": "sessions",
  "bootstrap_commands": [
    "SET LINESIZE 200",
    "SET PAGESIZE 1000",
    "SET SERVEROUTPUT ON",
    "SET SQLPROMPT '(Scribe) SQL> '"
  ],
  "aliases": {
    "cls": "CLEAR SCREEN",
    "clrscr": "CLEAR SCREEN",
    "wipe": "CLEAR SCREEN",
    "show tables": "SELECT table_name\nFROM user_tables\nORDER BY table_name;"
  },
  "ignore_export_commands": ["CLEAR SCREEN", "cls", "clrscr", "wipe"],
  "export": {
    "title": "Session"
  }
}
```

## Session Files

Each session produces three files under `sessions/`:

| File | Contents |
|---|---|
| `YYYY-MM-DD_HHMMSS.log` | Raw canonical transcript (never discarded) |
| `YYYY-MM-DD_HHMMSS.json` | Session metadata (commands, notes, exports) |
| `YYYY-MM-DD_HHMMSS.md` | Markdown export (generated by `/scribe export`) |

## Project Structure

```
scribe/
├── __init__.py       # Package init, version (0.1.0)
├── __main__.py       # Entry point: python -m scribe
├── cli.py            # Argument parser, main orchestrator
├── config.py         # Config dataclass, defaults, JSON load
├── elevation.py      # UAC elevation via PowerShell Start-Process
├── exporter.py       # Markdown export, history rendering
├── host.py           # Core ScribeHost: subprocess I/O, internal cmds
├── search.py         # Filesystem search over .log and .md files
└── session.py        # Session state/event dataclasses, JSON persistence
tests/
├── test_elevation.py
├── test_exporter.py
└── test_search.py
```

## Color Indicators (Future)

Color highlights can make session output easier to read at a glance. A future
version may support opt-in color for:

- **Scribe output** — internal command responses printed in a distinct color
- **SQL\*Plus errors** — lines matching `ORA-`, `SP2-`, etc. highlighted in red
- **Prompts** — the `(Scribe) SQL>` prompt in a subdued or branded color

Coloring would be controlled by a new `"ui"` section in `scribe.config.json`,
defaulting to off so the base experience is unchanged:

```json
{
  "ui": {
    "color": false,
    "scribe": "cyan",
    "error": "red",
    "prompt": "bright_black"
  }
}
```

A config-less run would continue to output plain text exactly as it does today.

## Requirements

- Python 3.10+
- Windows (primary; elevation and key-handling are Windows-specific)
- Oracle SQL\*Plus or any compatible command-line client
- No external Python dependencies (stdlib only)
